amily:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">he adequacy of the supervision by DCLG of the accreditation schemes.</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">”</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I can see no problems </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with the supervision of the accreditation schemes. The current problem is the lack of enforcement of the current rules by Local Authority Building Control departments</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (LABC’s)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Whilst these departments have a clear overview of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">new build projects, they have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> little</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> oversight of what work is being carried out within existing dwellings; and this is where the majority of “under the radar / cash in hand / non Part P compliant work” is being carried out.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> LABC departments should be carrying out spot checks on refur</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">bishments of existing dwellings to ensure compliance with the current rules </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> being adhered to, and taking action against those found to be avoiding compliance.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">SUMMARY</span></p><p style="font-size:1